navigationItems.name: Employee Certification Event Skill Performance Steps
Employee Certification Events
navigationItems.description: Individual certification records
navigationItems.documentation: Employee Certification Events capture the employee's performance measures for the selected Training Role at a point in time.  Typically the goal of the certification process is to see that the employee can not only meet the initial performance measures, such as throughput and quality percentage, but also improve those measures over the course of the certification process.

navigationItems.name: Skill Performance Steps
navigationItems.documentation: Skill Performance Steps allow you to document the exact steps that a person with knowledge of this skill should go through to adequately accomplish the skill.  These steps can be evaluated as part of an Employee / Training Role certification event.

navigationItems.name: Employee Certification Event Skill Performance Steps
How Do I Article
navigationItems.documentation: How do I articles, allow additional information about MQ1 Elements processes to be documented and maintained as part of the system.  The information in these articles can also show in the module user guide report.

navigationItems.name: QXtend Configs
navigationItems.documentation: QXtend configs holds the information and web service calls to configure the QAD QXtend product to work with MQ1 Elements.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Account Creation Setup
navigationItems.description: Used to configure required variables for supplier contact account creation.
navigationItems.documentation: This process is used to store the variables required for the functionality that automatically creates and emails supplier account information.

navigationItems.name: Domains
navigationItems.documentation: Domains are mostly used for data segregation/organization and ERP integration.  Domains are typically used to identify regions in the world, for example North America, EMEA or AsiaPac.  Domains provide a solution for an organization to execute from a single database, keeping the region data seperate by using Domains.  A similar technique would be to have a seperate MQ1 Elements installation/database for each region.

navigationItems.name: Entities
navigationItems.documentation: Entities are mostly used for data segregation/organization and ERP integration.  Entities are typically used to identify regions in the world, for example North America, EMEA or AsiaPac.  Entities provide a solution for an organization to execute from a single database, keeping the region data seperate by using Entities. A similar technique would be to have a seperate MQ1 Elements installation/database for each region.

navigationItems.name: Sites
navigationItems.documentation: Sites are used for organization, planning and inventory.  Each site typically correlates to a physical location, however a physical location could have more than one site. All inventory is stored by site and all planning is done by site. Each site should belong to one and only one entity, but an entity can have multiple sites.

navigationItems.name: Locations
navigationItems.documentation: Locations are where inventory is stored.  Each location belongs to a Site and a Site can have multiple locations.  Locations can include shelves, bins, tanks, silos, refrigerators, freezers, humidity and or temperature controlled rooms, segregated quarantine or material review areas, or other storage areas.

navigationItems.name: Generalized Codes
navigationItems.documentation: Generalized codes provides a method of defining acceptable values for fields and having the system validate user entry. Codes can display in a look-up for selection.

navigationItems.name: Generalized Code Types
navigationItems.documentation: Generalized code types are used to group generalized codes into logical units.  A generalized code type consists of one or more key value pairs that make up the generalized codes.  Examples of generalized code types include: Address types, process categories, and characteristic types.

navigationItems.name: Unit of Measures
navigationItems.documentation: Unit of measures help identify quantities when used throughout the application.  A conversion table is also assoicated with each unit of measure, allowing for the conversion factor to be defined when converting from one unit of measure to another.

navigationItems.name: Product Lines
navigationItems.documentation: Product lines are used to group/classify items or products with similar characteristics.  Usually the grouping is by similarities of manufacture, use, application, cost analysis, or revenue analysis.

navigationItems.name: Item Groups
navigationItems.documentation: Item groups allow you to subdivide product lines.  Items are often grouped based on similar characteristics, such as end user function.  For Items that are purchased, item groups might be created for each commodity type

navigationItems.name: Item Types
navigationItems.documentation: Item types are the most general grouping level for Items.  Item Types are generally used to distinguish between Items that are purchased versus Items that are manufactured, although there may be additional Item Types to help break down a very large Item database.  Examples of Item Types might be Finished Good, Component, Purchased Product, Spare Part, etc.

navigationItems.name: Departments
navigationItems.documentation: Departments split a site into groups for control purposes.  Departments are used to group things like work centers and processes.

navigationItems.name: Work Centers
navigationItems.documentation: Work centers are a specific production until within a department.  Each department may have one or more work centers.  Work centers are typically involved setting up routing or process flow information and in maintenance activities.  Work centers consist of people and machines.

navigationItems.name: Management System Standards
navigationItems.documentation: Management System Standards, based on a web definition, are a framework of processes and procedures used to ensure that an organization can fulfill all the tasks required to achieve its objectives.  Examples include: ISO 9001, ISO 14001, OHSAS 18001, ISO 13485, and GxP.  For each management system standard defined, one or more sections of the standard can also be defined.  Audit questions can be associated with management system standards and/or sections to help when reviewing auditing coverage.

navigationItems.name: Review Frequencies
navigationItems.description: Frequencies that drive review requirements
navigationItems.documentation: Review frequencies are used to create re-usable frequencies for items that expire, for example skill re-training or document review.  Upon expiration, action messages are often generated to the appropriate personnel to determine the next steps for the item should be.  For skill re-training, this may mean to create a training event and train the employees who require training.  For a document review, this may mean to either update the document to make it more relevant or make it obsolete if it's no longer used.

navigationItems.name: Company Types
navigationItems.documentation: Company types allow for organizating companies.  Some examples of company types are: Customer, Supplier, and Professional.

navigationItems.name: Cost Accounts
navigationItems.documentation: Cost accounts are typically tied to the general ledger and allow you to associate costs with the groups defined on the general ledger for cost tracking purposes.

navigationItems.name: Shifts
navigationItems.documentation: Shifts are used to identify different periods of a single day when work is being completed.  Requirements of management system standards often refer to ensuring that an organization with multiple shifts not forget the other shifts in the organization for activities such as training and auditing.  This shifts process simply adds a list of shifts that can then be used on Audits, for example, to identify which shift or shifts were audited, this information can then later be used during other audits to prove that each shift has been audited as required.

navigationItems.name: Projects
navigationItems.documentation: APQP Projects are used to track the tasks, checklists, and approvals associated with launching a new product or making a change to an existing product.

navigationItems.name: Manufacturing Documents
navigationItems.description: Customer specific part information.
navigationItems.documentation: Manufacturing Documents provide controlled copies of documentation used for the manufacture of an Item.  Typically these documents would include the process flow, process FMEA, process control plan, and additional work instructions.  If worksheets are used, manufacturing documents can be created from a worksheet allowing you to quickly create the documentation required for a given item.

navigationItems.name: PPAP Submissions
navigationItems.description: PPAP Submission records, used to generate PPAPs and Warrants
navigationItems.documentation: PPAP Submissions are used to track submissions to your customer as part of the production part approval process (PPAP).

navigationItems.name: Drawings
navigationItems.description: Controlled drawing files and feature lists
navigationItems.documentation: Drawings are used by engineering to control the CAD drawings typically associated with products or items.  It is recommended that the CAD drawings are loaded as PDF files to allow approval routing and reference use when creating production documentation.  PDF files are recommended because typically engineering departments have their own file management system which integrates into their design environment for managing all of the files that could make up a single CAD drawing.  Drawings differ from Documents in that they allow you to define specifications associated with the Drawing.  These specifications will then be available to "import" into a manufacturing documentation worksheet so that the proper control information can be established when producing the Process Control Plan.

navigationItems.name: Meetings
navigationItems.description: Meetings are used to document the results of key meetings within the organization. Meetings could be used to document the following: Yearly Management Review, New Product Development projects, Cross Functional Team meetings related to CAPA and NCRs.

navigationItems.name: Items
navigationItems.documentation: Items identify things that you stock in inventory, purchase, manufacture, sell, or service. Items can identify raw materials, purchased or manufactured intermediates, finished items, packaging materials, planning items, configured products, service kits, and repair parts used in service activities.

navigationItems.name: Programs
navigationItems.documentation: Programs are used to define a standardized list of program codes and names. Programs are typically created by large organizations to identify a large project that many include many smaller projects. In the automotive vertical, often you'll see programs associated with future model builds of a particular vehicle, such as the 2020 Ford Bronco.

navigationItems.name: Processes
navigationItems.description: Manufacturing processes, used in APQP process flows.
navigationItems.documentation: Generally processes should be documented in terms of three categories: Customer Oriented Processes - are core processes to the business (design & development, order management, production, etc.), Management Oriented Processes - are processes that define areas of management responsibility and typically have an indirect impact on the customer (quality policy & objectives, resource management, planning, etc.), and Support Oriented Processes - are all other processes that enable the other process defined (purchasing, finance, information technology, etc.).  Having the processes documented helps in several areas including Auditing, Product design and Development and Corrective Action and Non-conformance.

navigationItems.name: Library Specifications
navigationItems.documentation: Specifications document the acceptance criteria, including where appropriate the tolerances of an attribute or characteristic.  Each specification is associated with a Specification Group, as well as linked to additional data (Item, Process, Drawing, etc.) which defines the applicability of the specification.

navigationItems.name: Control Library
navigationItems.description: A library of control methods for specifications.
navigationItems.documentation: A library of methods used to control quality related to product or process specifications. These can then be brought in to manufacturing documents.

navigationItems.name: PFMEA Failure Analysis Library
navigationItems.description: Process FMEA Library

navigationItems.name: Family Templates
navigationItems.description: Generic part production information
navigationItems.documentation: A "Family Template" is essentially a non-part-specific Manufacturing Document that can be used to create Manufacturing Documents. You may think of it as a Manufacturing Document Template. A "Family Template" will house the FMEA, Process Flow, Control Plans, and Specifications for a product "family" which can be used as a starting point for new Manufacturing Documents.

navigationItems.name: PPAP Submission Requirement Sets
navigationItems.description: Sets of required information for PPAP submissions
navigationItems.documentation: PPAP Submission Requirement Sets defines groups of PPAP requirements per customer.

navigationItems.name: Project Roles Library
navigationItems.documentation: A project role defines a label of a job responsibility specific for a project (note these are different than training roles and are only used for project assignment and/or approval). Examples of a project role might be: Project Manager, Design Engineer, or Quality Engineer.

navigationItems.name: PPAP Requirement Status
navigationItems.documentation: PPAP Requirment status' are used to define the status of the link between a PPAP requirement and a PPAP level.  Examples are S = the organization shall submit, R = the organization shall retain, and * = the organization shall retain and submit upon request.

navigationItems.name: Drawing Types
navigationItems.documentation: Drawing Types provide a general grouping of drawings.  Drawing types are also used to setup the default list of approvers for a type of drawing.  Drawing types could be setup by the different types of products being created or even by the different areas of the engineering department.  Another example for the use of drawing types is the source of the drawing, for example Customer and/or Supplier drawings.

navigationItems.name: Item Types
navigationItems.documentation: Item types are the most general grouping level for Items.  Item Types are generally used to distinguish between Items that are purchased versus Items that are manufactured, although there may be additional Item Types to help break down a very large Item database.  Examples of Item Types might be Finished Good, Component, Purchased Product, Spare Part, etc.

navigationItems.name: Item Groups
navigationItems.documentation: Item groups allow you to subdivide product lines.  Items are often grouped based on similar characteristics, such as end user function.  For Items that are purchased, item groups might be created for each commodity type

navigationItems.name: PPAP Requirements
navigationItems.documentation: PPAP requirements define a full list of requirements for PPAP submission.  The default list comes from the AIAG (Automotive Industry Action Group) PPAP manual, but customer specific requirements can be added to the list as requried.

navigationItems.name: Issue Categories
navigationItems.documentation: Issue categories allow you to define a logical grouping for issues. Examples of issue categories might be: Tooling, Process, Material, Gauging, etc.

navigationItems.name: Product Lines
navigationItems.documentation: Product lines are used to group/classify items or products with similar characteristics.  Usually the grouping is by similarities of manufacture, use, application, cost analysis, or revenue analysis.

navigationItems.name: Meeting Types
navigationItems.documentation: Meeting types allow you to define a logical grouping for meetings and also set up the default agenda for a meeting. Examples of meeting types might be: Monthly Quality Review, Quarterly Scorecard Review, or Yearly Management Review

navigationItems.name: Specification Categories
navigationItems.documentation: Specification categories allow you to group specification by a common name, typically for presentation on a report such as a certificate of conformity or certificate of analysis.  Examples of categories might be Electrical Properties, Physical Properties, or Chemical Analysis.

navigationItems.name: Specification Names
navigationItems.description: Names of common specifications
navigationItems.documentation: Specification Names allow you to provide consistency with specification naming to help avoid naming problems such as having many different values that really mean the same thing.  For example it's common to see a value such as width be entered as a specification as width, widths, wd, or w.  To help avoid this problem, the specification names process was created to provide a level of security control over who can create specification names.

navigationItems.name: Specification Date Ranges
navigationItems.documentation: Used to define the acceptable number of days for specifications that use the type Date.  For example, the name of the range might be 1 year and the number of days would then be 365.

navigationItems.name: Special Symbols
navigationItems.documentation: Special symbols allow you to create unique images that are typically used to identify special characteristics or failure modes.

navigationItems.name: Process Symbols
navigationItems.documentation: Process symbols allow you to create a library of process images or symbols that can be used on reports as an indicator of the process, for example on the process flow report.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Severity Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Design FMEA severity criteria table is used when creating a DesignFMEA.  The severity ratings are a relative indication of how severe an effect is to the customer if it happens.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Occurrence Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Design FMEA occurrence criteria table is used when creating a Design FMEA.  The occurrence ratings are a relative indication of how likely a failure mode is to happen.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Detection Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Design FMEA detection criteria table is used when creating a Design FMEA.  The detection ratings are a relative indication of how likely a current control is going to detect a failure mode if it happens.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Occurrence Zone
navigationItems.documentation: Associated with the RPL method of identifying risk, this process defines all of the combinations of severity and occurrence and assigns each a priority level.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Detection Zone
navigationItems.documentation: Associated with the RPL method of identifying risk, this process defines all of the combinations of severity and detection and assigns each a priority level.

navigationItems.name: Design FMEA Priority Levels
navigationItems.documentation: Associated with the RPL method of identifying risk, this process defines all of the combinations of the occurrence zone and detection zone and assigns each a priority level.  The result of identifying where in this matrix that a failure falls is the assigned RPL.

navigationItems.name: Process FMEA Severity Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Process FMEA severity criteria table is used when creating a Process FMEA.  The severity ratings are a relative indication of how severe an effect is to the customer if it happens.

navigationItems.name: Process FMEA Occurrence Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Process FMEA occurrence criteria table is used when creating a Process FMEA.  The occurrence ratings are a relative indication of how likely a failure mode is to happen.

navigationItems.name: Process FMEA Detection Criteria
navigationItems.documentation: The Process FMEA detection criteria table is used when creating a Process FMEA.  The detection ratings are a relative indication of how likely a current control is going to detect a failure mode if it happens.

navigationItems.name: Process FMEA Detection Zone
navigationItems.documentation: Associated with the RPL method of identifying risk, this process defines all of the combinations of severity and detection and assigns each a priority level.

navigationItems.name: Process FMEA Priority Levels
navigationItems.documentation: Associated with the RPL method of identifying risk, this process defines all of the combinations of the occurrence zone and detection zone and assigns each a priority level.  The result of identifying where in this matrix that a failure falls is the assigned RPL.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Types
navigationItems.description: Methods of inspection sampling
navigationItems.documentation: Indicates the method of sampling for inspection, such as pre-production, first run, etc...

navigationItems.name: Inspection Stations
navigationItems.documentation: Inspection Stations are used to identify locations where inspections take place.  Control Plan items can be assigned one or more inspection stations and then can be used to limit which control plan items show up for an inspection event based on a selected station.

navigationItems.name: PFMEA Control Methods
navigationItems.description: Methods of detection and prevention of failure
navigationItems.documentation: Control methods allow you to provide consistency with control method naming.

navigationItems.name: Reaction Plans
navigationItems.documentation: Reaction plans is a simple process that allows you to define a list of standard reaction plans that can then be used when defining controls for inspection.

navigationItems.name: Sample Sizes
navigationItems.documentation: Sample sizes is a simple process that allows you to define a list of standard sample sizes both from a numeric value and a alphanumeric value that can then be used when defining controls for inspection.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Types
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge types allow you to categorize gauges that have similar characteristics.  Examples could be micrometer, caliper, or plug gauge.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Sub-Types
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge sub-types allow you to further categorize gauges.  Gauges of the same sub-type should have the same calibration standards.

navigationItems.name: Gauges
navigationItems.description: Gauge tracking and calibration information
navigationItems.documentation: Gauges is where the list of gauging is maintained.  Gauges are organized by type and sub-type.  Gauge type is used to define the calibration procedure for the gauge, and sub-type is used to define the calibration standards for the gauge.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment Types
navigationItems.documentation: Equipment types allow you to categorize equipment that have similar characteristics.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment
navigationItems.documentation: Equipment allows you to document the pieces of equipment in the organization.  Typically the equipment also contains the associated maintenance information, both preventive and reactive for tracking purposes.

navigationItems.name: Unit of Measures
navigationItems.documentation: Unit of measures help identify quantities when used throughout the application.  A conversion table is also assoicated with each unit of measure, allowing for the conversion factor to be defined when converting from one unit of measure to another.

navigationItems.name: Management System Standards
navigationItems.documentation: Management System Standards, based on a web definition, are a framework of processes and procedures used to ensure that an organization can fulfill all the tasks required to achieve its objectives.  Examples include: ISO 9001, ISO 14001, OHSAS 18001, ISO 13485, and GxP.  For each management system standard defined, one or more sections of the standard can also be defined.  Audit questions can be associated with management system standards and/or sections to help when reviewing auditing coverage.

navigationItems.name: Audits
navigationItems.description: Individual audit records
navigationItems.documentation: Auditing the processes and procedures that make up the quality or management system is a vital part in ensuring that they system is functioning as designed.  The Audits process is designed to support the planning and documenting of all types of audits, including but not limited to the following: First party (internal) compliance and process audits, Second party (supplier) compliance and process audits, Safety and Environmental audits, and Third party (independent auditor) conformance audits.  The full results, as well as any audit findings can be documented and summarized with this process.

navigationItems.name: LPA Group
navigationItems.description: Groups consisting of audit layers
navigationItems.documentation: LPA Group provides a general group of Audits and or LPAs.

navigationItems.name: Audit Results
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Results allow auditors to document the result and any observations made for each question asked during the audit.  Audit Results are then typically totalled or averaged to be used as a comparison to other areas within the organization.

navigationItems.name: Audit Findings
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Findings allow an auditor to document any observations, opportunities for improvement, or noteworthy efforts that are noticed during the audit.  Audit findings do not include non-conformances that are found during an audit, they are documented under the non-conformance section of the audit.

navigationItems.name: Audit Checklist
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Checklists allow you to group one or more Audit Questions into a checklists that can be used on an Audit or Layered Process Audit.

navigationItems.name: Audit Questions
navigationItems.description: Standardized questions for audits.
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Questions, allow for users to create a standard list of questions used for the various auditing scenarios.  Audit Questions can be grouped by several factors including Audit Type, Management System Standard, and Process.

navigationItems.name: Processes
navigationItems.description: Manufacturing processes, used in APQP process flows.
navigationItems.documentation: Generally processes should be documented in terms of three categories: Customer Oriented Processes - are core processes to the business (design & development, order management, production, etc.), Management Oriented Processes - are processes that define areas of management responsibility and typically have an indirect impact on the customer (quality policy & objectives, resource management, planning, etc.), and Support Oriented Processes - are all other processes that enable the other process defined (purchasing, finance, information technology, etc.).  Having the processes documented helps in several areas including Auditing, Product design and Development and Corrective Action and Non-conformance.

navigationItems.name: Audit Types
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Types provide a general group of audits.  Typical examples of audit types are: Process - focused on one or more processes, Complaince - focused on regulatory requirements and typically completed by government agencies, or Conformance - system audit that is typically completed by a third party registrar.

navigationItems.name: Audit Finding Types
navigationItems.documentation: Audit Finding Types allow you to organize different finds for an audit.  Typically there are at least three different audit finding types: Praises, Observations, and Opportunities for Improvement.  A fourth type of audit finding is also very common, the Non-conformance, but these are logged as nonconformances themselves, rather than logging an Audit Finding.

navigationItems.name: Complaints
navigationItems.documentation: This complaints process is a front end to the Adverse Events process. This process is designed to capture the complaint information, complete an assessment, document actions/containment/disposition activities, correspondence, and closure of the complaint. This process is designed for either life science or non-life science companies. The process tabs include General, Complainant, and Event Information, which are used to document initial information about the issue. The Assessment tab is used to review other quality events that may be related, categorizing the issue, and escalating to other processes as deemed necessary. The Actions tab docuemnts and tracks actions and containment/disposition activities. The Correspondence tab is used to document customer correspondance, and is a centralized place to add photos or file attachments. The Closure tab documents the final resolution and closure of the process.

navigationItems.name: Complaints Problem Severity
navigationItems.description: Complaints Problem Severity is used to categorize complaints by its severity, assign state durations, and if CAPA is required based on the severity level.

navigationItems.name: Sales Order Setup
navigationItems.description: This process is used to search/lookup Item(s) based on its Sales Order. By selecting the Item associated with the sales order it will populate the Item(s) field on the Complaints/General tab. Because of the possibility of having to manage potentially hundreds of thousands/millions of sales orders, this process would most likely be used in conjunction with an integration with an ERP system.

navigationItems.name: Serial Numbers
navigationItems.description: This process is used to search/lookup Item(s) based on its serial number. By selecting the Item associated with the serial number in the search it will populate the Item(s) field on the Complaints/General tab. Because of the possibility of having to manage potentially hundreds of thousands/millions of serial numbers this process would likely be used in conjunction with an integration with an ERP system.

navigationItems.name: Adverse Events
navigationItems.description: The Adverse Events process is the main process of the Adverse Events Module. This process is used to capture the initial intake information, as well as be the main container for all of the additional information related to the Adverse Event, such as Non-conformances, Additional Tasks, FDA submissions, etc.

navigationItems.name: Adverse Events Reportability Assessment Response
navigationItems.description: The Reportability Assessment Response process is used to store the response to a Reportability Assessment question for a Adverse Event.

navigationItems.name: Adverse Events Tasks
navigationItems.description: Adverse Event tasks are used to drive the Adverse Event investigation process. Once a Adverse Event is initially approved, a set of predetermined tasks will automatically be created for the Adverse Event to ensure all of the investigation tasks are completed. If additional tasks are required for a specific Adverse Event, ad hoc tasks can be created by the Adverse Event Specialist or Adverse Event Coordinator.

navigationItems.name: MDR Library Tasks
navigationItems.description: Library tasks are used to define a list of tasks that should be completed for each complaint. Using tasks ensures that steps required to investigate a complaint are not missed and are completed in a timely manner.

navigationItems.name: MDR Library Tasks Categories
navigationItems.description: Library task categories provide a method to group library tasks, and therefore tasks associated with a Complaint. Some examples of categories may be: Sample Evaluation, Clinical Assessment, Lot History Review, Labeling Review, etc.

navigationItems.name: MDR Reportability Questions
navigationItems.description: Reportability questions provide the ability to assist the Complaints team in determining the reportability of any given complaint. Typically there are many points on the decision tree that help to identify if a complaint must be reported to a reporting agency, such as the FDA. The questions entered in this setup process will be displayed for every complaint, and then responded to for every complaint.

navigationItems.name: MDR Event Outcomes
navigationItems.description: Event outcomes are descriptions used when completing the intake of the complaint to identify what action(s) were taken by the reporting person or associated team. The FDA MDR defines several outcomes in section B2. Serious outcomes, including death, can be flagged to notify top management whenever they occur.

navigationItems.name: MDR Follow-up Types
navigationItems.description: Follow-up types are used to categorize the reason for a submission follow-up.

navigationItems.name: MDR Reportable Event Types
navigationItems.description: Reportable event types allow you to define the selectable values when identify the type of event for a Complaint. According to the FORM FDA 3500A, there are 3 types of reportable events: Death, Serious Injury, and Malfunction.

navigationItems.name: MDR Library Task Responsibility Types
navigationItems.description: Library tasks responsibility types, is a system controlled process that defines a list of types used to control how a task for a complaint has the responsibility field set automatically. Automatically setting the responsibility field ensures that all tasks are immediately assigned and don't "fall through the cracks." This list is controlled by the system, because each value provides different functionality that is controlled by the configuration. The acceptable values are: Complaint Specialist, Complaint Coordinator, Security Role, and Employee.

navigationItems.name: MDR Remedial Action Types
navigationItems.description: Remedial action types are used to identify if any remedial action has been initiated based on the complaint. The MedWatch 3500A form lists several different types, including "other" at which point the Other Remedial Action field is filled in.

navigationItems.name: MDR Submission Types
navigationItems.description: Submission types determine the type of report that is being submitted.

navigationItems.name: Item Inventory
navigationItems.documentation: Item inventory documents the quantity of inventory at a location for an item.  Inventory transactions can be used to document and adjust the inventory at a location.

navigationItems.name: Adverse Events Submissions
navigationItems.description: Adverse Event submissions are used to track the submission(s) to reporting agencies such as the U.S. FDA. Submissions can be created manually, for the case where automated submissions are not supported, or automatically.

navigationItems.name: FDA Evaluation Codes
navigationItems.description: When responding to an MDR, one of the sections requires describing the method, result and conclusion of any evaluations via specific codes provided by the reporting agencies. The FDA Evaluation Codes process allows you to setup the codes within the system so they're easily selectable when completing a Complaint.
navigationItems.documentation: FDA Evaluation Codes list the values that shall be selected when submitting a Medical Device Report (MDR).

navigationItems.name: FDA Event Problem Codes
navigationItems.description: When responding to an MDR, one of the sections requires describing the patient and device/component problems via specific codes provided by the reporting agencies. The FDA Event Problem Codes process allows you to setup the codes within the system so they're easily selectable when completing a Complaint.
navigationItems.documentation: FDA Problem Codes list the values that shall be selected when submitting a Medical Device Report (MDR).

navigationItems.name: Documents
navigationItems.description: Controlled document records
navigationItems.documentation: Controlled documents are one of the most important pieces of a quality management system. This Documents process is used to control the policies and procedures that are used throughout the organization. A controlled document is subject to a secure review and approval process to ensure content integrity. MQ1 Elements provides the features necessary for simple and very complex document management processes. The ability to attach a file, which is also controlled, means that you can modify the content associated with a document using the content editor of your choice. You can set up automatic file content conversion to PDF for the following file types: Microsoft Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and Visio. Each document follows a standard work flow as the document progresses from draft to official to obsolete, and so on. As the work flow of a document is completed, various action manager messages are generated to ensure that people responsible for task and for approval are notified and aware of the impending action. Official documents are the current controlled official version of a document that can be referred to during associated work.  When a new document is made official, the previous versions are set to obsolete. This helps ensure that people always have the correct official version of a document. The document control process is also linked to the training management system, which allows for the creation of training notifications and events for each version change to a document (if training is needed.)

navigationItems.name: Change Requests
navigationItems.description: Requests to change one or more documents
navigationItems.documentation: A document change request allows you to record a request for a change to a document, allowing the document owner to decide whether to initiate a change to the document.

navigationItems.name: Document Hardcopy
navigationItems.description: Tracking information for physical copies of documents
navigationItems.documentation: Document hard copies allow you to document and then later retrieve, copies of a document that have been issued to individuals or locations.  When a document has a new version available, the document hard copy list can then be used to ensure that previous old versions of the document are collected and therefore no longer used.

navigationItems.name: Records
navigationItems.description: Uncontrolled documents
navigationItems.documentation: Records allow users to track and store information about quality system records, which are often filled out versions of a form, that allow you to provide proof of a business event.  Records typically differ from Documents in that they don't require an approval process.  Some examples of a record might be Management Review Meetings, Training records, evidence related to Product realization, evidence to structured problem solving and Internal Audits.  MQ1 Elements provides many of these processes for you, so items that would be documented here in the Records process would be business events that require proof where MQ1 Elements does not have the process available.

navigationItems.name: Manuals
navigationItems.description: Collections of related documents
navigationItems.documentation: Manuals allow you to group Documents together.  For example, manuals might be created for each department in the organization that links all of the documents together that a person may need for the department.  The concept of manuals originated in the days where documents were mainly paper based.  Manuals in this case were typically a three ring binder of paper which represented all of the document of the manual, again used for organization purposes.  Because manuals are typically only used to group similar documents, often adding the appropriate fields to the Documents process can replace the need of manuals.  For example the department field on the Documents process can be used to identify which department(s) a document belongs too.  Using this technique, the Documents become self organizing reducing the effort required to maintain manuals.

navigationItems.name: Document Types
navigationItems.description: Categorizes and sets default properties for Documents.
navigationItems.documentation: Document Types provide a way to group documents and setup various options for each document associated with the Document types, such as the number of days to approve, a list of editors, a list of viewers, and a list of approvers. Examples of document types may include: Quality System Procedures, Standard Operating Procedures, and Work Instructions.

navigationItems.name: Document Templates
navigationItems.description: Standardized documents used to create document records.
navigationItems.documentation: Document templates allow users to have a starting point file.  For example there might be a document template for a Standard Operating Procedure, which has headings in place for Purpose, Scope and Procedure along with the standard company header.  Having document templates allow users to focus more on writing content and less on format.

navigationItems.name: Document Change Categories
navigationItems.documentation: Document Change Categories provide a way to group changes based on what needs to be done and who needs to approve. Each category provides the ability to setup a checklist to help guide change and a list of approvers that become level one approvers for the document change.

navigationItems.name: Record Types
navigationItems.description: Default options for records, such as file storage locations and dispoal information
navigationItems.documentation: Record types are used as an organizational unit for grouping records of similar characteristics.  Examples of record types might be: Purchase Orders, work orders, or certificates.

navigationItems.name: Review Frequencies
navigationItems.description: Frequencies that drive review requirements
navigationItems.documentation: Review frequencies are used to create re-usable frequencies for items that expire, for example skill re-training or document review.  Upon expiration, action messages are often generated to the appropriate personnel to determine the next steps for the item should be.  For skill re-training, this may mean to create a training event and train the employees who require training.  For a document review, this may mean to either update the document to make it more relevant or make it obsolete if it's no longer used.

navigationItems.name: Employees
navigationItems.description: Employee Skills & General Information
navigationItems.documentation: Employees document the information for each employee in the organization.  Each employee can also have their training information documented as part of the employee record.

navigationItems.name: Customers
navigationItems.documentation: Customers allow you to document information about your customers.

navigationItems.name: Items
navigationItems.documentation: Items identify things that you stock in inventory, purchase, manufacture, sell, or service. Items can identify raw materials, purchased or manufactured intermediates, finished items, packaging materials, planning items, configured products, service kits, and repair parts used in service activities.

navigationItems.name: Contacts
navigationItems.documentation: Contacts allow you to document information about people who are external to the organization.

navigationItems.name: Correspondence
navigationItems.documentation: Correspondence allows you to document a conversation or e-mail message that you had with a contact.

navigationItems.name: Suppliers
navigationItems.documentation: Suppliers allow you to document information about your suppliers.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Items
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier items allow you to document the relationship between an Item and a Supplier.  The relationship allows you to also indicate additional information such as the supplier's catalog or item number as well as a standard price.

navigationItems.name: Company Types
navigationItems.documentation: Company types allow for organizating companies.  Some examples of company types are: Customer, Supplier, and Professional.

navigationItems.name: Companies
navigationItems.documentation: Companies are used to document information about the organizations that this organization has a relationship with.  The Companies process is generic, where there are specific processes for Customer and Supplier relationship information.

navigationItems.name: Contact Groups
navigationItems.documentation: Contact Groups offer a way to organize a set of contacts.

navigationItems.name: Projects
navigationItems.documentation: APQP Projects are used to track the tasks, checklists, and approvals associated with launching a new product or making a change to an existing product.

navigationItems.name: Lessons Learned
navigationItems.documentation: Lessons learned is a common concept in most organizations.  They can be used to document and manage lessons that people have learned either through the solving of a problem or the completion of an improvement.  The lessons can also be reviewed periodically to ensure they're still relevant to the organization.  During certain planning activities, lessons learned should be reviewed to ensure they're incorporated into the activities being planned.

navigationItems.name: Meetings
navigationItems.description: Meetings are used to document the results of key meetings within the organization. Meetings could be used to document the following: Yearly Management Review, New Product Development projects, Cross Functional Team meetings related to CAPA and NCRs.

navigationItems.name: Issue Resolutions
navigationItems.documentation: Issue Resolutions allow you to define a list of resolution codes for when an Issue associated with an APQPproject is completed. By defining a standardized list of resolution codes and then assigning a single code to an Issue, you'll have a way to categorize and analyze how Issues associated with APQP projects are being resolved.

navigationItems.name: Issue On Hold Reasons
navigationItems.documentation: Issue OnHold Reasons allow you to define a standardized list of reasons why an Issue may be on hold. By selecting a single reason on an Issue at the On Hold state, you can then quickly analyze the potential roadblock stopping the Issue from being completed.

navigationItems.name: Issue Categories
navigationItems.documentation: Issue categories allow you to define a logical grouping for issues. Examples of issue categories might be: Tooling, Process, Material, Gauging, etc.

navigationItems.name: Meeting Types
navigationItems.documentation: Meeting types allow you to define a logical grouping for meetings and also set up the default agenda for a meeting. Examples of meeting types might be: Monthly Quality Review, Quarterly Scorecard Review, or Yearly Management Review

navigationItems.name: Project Roles Library
navigationItems.documentation: A project role defines a label of a job responsibility specific for a project (note these are different than training roles and are only used for project assignment and/or approval). Examples of a project role might be: Project Manager, Design Engineer, or Quality Engineer.

navigationItems.name: Project Tasks Library
navigationItems.description: Library tasks for new product development groups.

navigationItems.name: Project Gates Library
navigationItems.documentation: APQP Library Gates define the list of gates that APQP projects typically go though. Generally a gate (sometimes also called a phase) is used as a transition point in the APQPproject and requires an approval from many members of the project team to proceed.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Calibrations
navigationItems.description: This process helps maintain the the calibration of gauges by tracking calibration schedules for gauges that use calendar-based calibration (Scheduled Calibration) and gauges that are calibrated based on a set number of uses (Usage-Based Calibration).

navigationItems.name: Gauge Studies
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge R&R studies are used as a measurement systems analysis technique and help to identify possible sources (equipment, people, process, samples, environment, etc.) of variation in the measurement system.

navigationItems.name: Gauges
navigationItems.description: Gauge tracking and calibration information
navigationItems.documentation: Gauges is where the list of gauging is maintained.  Gauges are organized by type and sub-type.  Gauge type is used to define the calibration procedure for the gauge, and sub-type is used to define the calibration standards for the gauge.

navigationItems.name: Cost Logs
navigationItems.documentation: Cost Log records document the occurrence of a cost to the organization, typically for helping to determine a cost of quality metric.  A cost log entry can be made from several processes including Maintenance Work Orders and Containment Actions.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Status
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge status' define the list of acceptable status for a gauge.  Each status allows you to define if the gauge will be considered active or inactive that will automatically set the state of the gauge to active or inactive.  Examples of gauge status' might include: Out for Calibration, Missing, or Scrapped.

navigationItems.name: Asset Usage Log
navigationItems.documentation: The asset usage log documents usage for assets such as equipment and gauges.  The information entered into the log can then be used with asset meters to create preventive maintenance work orders.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Types
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge types allow you to categorize gauges that have similar characteristics.  Examples could be micrometer, caliper, or plug gauge.

navigationItems.name: Gauge Sub-Types
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge sub-types allow you to further categorize gauges.  Gauges of the same sub-type should have the same calibration standards.

navigationItems.name: Cost Accounts
navigationItems.documentation: Cost accounts are typically tied to the general ledger and allow you to associate costs with the groups defined on the general ledger for cost tracking purposes.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Stations
navigationItems.documentation: Inspection Stations are used to identify locations where inspections take place.  Control Plan items can be assigned one or more inspection stations and then can be used to limit which control plan items show up for an inspection event based on a selected station.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Types
navigationItems.description: Methods of inspection sampling
navigationItems.documentation: Indicates the method of sampling for inspection, such as pre-production, first run, etc...

navigationItems.name: Drawings
navigationItems.description: Controlled drawing files and feature lists
navigationItems.documentation: Drawings are used by engineering to control the CAD drawings typically associated with products or items.  It is recommended that the CAD drawings are loaded as PDF files to allow approval routing and reference use when creating production documentation.  PDF files are recommended because typically engineering departments have their own file management system which integrates into their design environment for managing all of the files that could make up a single CAD drawing.  Drawings differ from Documents in that they allow you to define specifications associated with the Drawing.  These specifications will then be available to "import" into a manufacturing documentation worksheet so that the proper control information can be established when producing the Process Control Plan.

navigationItems.name: Drawing Types
navigationItems.documentation: Drawing Types provide a general grouping of drawings.  Drawing types are also used to setup the default list of approvers for a type of drawing.  Drawing types could be setup by the different types of products being created or even by the different areas of the engineering department.  Another example for the use of drawing types is the source of the drawing, for example Customer and/or Supplier drawings.

navigationItems.name: Items
navigationItems.documentation: Items identify things that you stock in inventory, purchase, manufacture, sell, or service. Items can identify raw materials, purchased or manufactured intermediates, finished items, packaging materials, planning items, configured products, service kits, and repair parts used in service activities.

navigationItems.name: Item Types
navigationItems.documentation: Item types are the most general grouping level for Items.  Item Types are generally used to distinguish between Items that are purchased versus Items that are manufactured, although there may be additional Item Types to help break down a very large Item database.  Examples of Item Types might be Finished Good, Component, Purchased Product, Spare Part, etc.

navigationItems.name: Item Groups
navigationItems.documentation: Item groups allow you to subdivide product lines.  Items are often grouped based on similar characteristics, such as end user function.  For Items that are purchased, item groups might be created for each commodity type

navigationItems.name: Product Lines
navigationItems.documentation: Product lines are used to group/classify items or products with similar characteristics.  Usually the grouping is by similarities of manufacture, use, application, cost analysis, or revenue analysis.

navigationItems.name: Sample Sizes
navigationItems.documentation: Sample sizes is a simple process that allows you to define a list of standard sample sizes both from a numeric value and a alphanumeric value that can then be used when defining controls for inspection.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Event Results
navigationItems.description: Results of a single set of inspection measurements.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Events
navigationItems.description: Groups of inspection results.
navigationItems.documentation: Inspection events store the results of an inspection that has been completed.  The definition of what is being inspected on an inspection event is pulled from the control plan of a Manufacturing Document.

navigationItems.name: Inspection Event Questions
navigationItems.description: Created by control plan and cavity records, feeds the inspection event checklist field.

navigationItems.name: Inventory Status Codes
navigationItems.documentation: Inventory status codes are used to indicate the current status of inventory at a location.  Status codes are typically used by ERP applications to determine whether inventory is available for use or not.  Inventory may not be available for use if it's non-conforming for example.

navigationItems.name: Non-conformances
navigationItems.description: Processe(s) or product(s) not conforming to specifications.
navigationItems.documentation: Nonconformances are used to identify product(s) or process(s) that are not conforming to their identified specifications.  After being identified, nonconformances can then be dispositioned to determine what action(s) should be done to resolve the nonconformance.  Nonconformances are also an excellent source of trending problems happening in the organization.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Corrective Action Request
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier corrective action requests allow you to issue and track the status of corrective actions that have been issued to suppliers.

navigationItems.name: Quality Alerts
navigationItems.documentation: Quality alerts are way to communicate quality related issues or deviations throughout the organization.  After being created, quality alerts can be displayed electronically on other processes, such as on Inspection events so that users can quickly see active alerts.  Once alerts reach their expiration date they can automatically be removed from lists.

navigationItems.name: Deviations
navigationItems.description: Documentation for deviations on controlled specifications or processes.
navigationItems.documentation: Deviations are used to document and approve changes to the standards used by the organization.  A deviation generally affects an item or a process, changing temporarily one or more specifications associated with the item or the way the process is completed.  Deviations can then be approved either internally and/or by the customer to begin the change.  Typically, deviations then expire based on time or when a certain number of items have been produced under the deviation.

navigationItems.name: Improvements
navigationItems.documentation: Improvements are used to document and manage ideas to improve areas of the organization.  Often, improvements can be thought of as an electronic suggestion box.  If accepted, an improvement can be tracked through completion using actions associated with the improvement.

navigationItems.name: Problem Solving Tasks
navigationItems.documentation: Problem solving tasks are used to assign someone a task that is related to completing a Nonconformance, Corrective Action, Improvement or a customer complaint.  The tasks typically define a specific piece of work that must be completed in order to implement a corrective action plan or prevention plan that is associated with a Nonconformance, Corrective Action, Improvement or Customer Complaint.

navigationItems.name: Lessons Learned
navigationItems.documentation: Lessons learned is a common concept in most organizations.  They can be used to document and manage lessons that people have learned either through the solving of a problem or the completion of an improvement.  The lessons can also be reviewed periodically to ensure they're still relevant to the organization.  During certain planning activities, lessons learned should be reviewed to ensure they're incorporated into the activities being planned.

navigationItems.name: Receiving Item Log
navigationItems.documentation: The receiving item log is used to document receipts from suppliers.  This information can be used in conjunction with non-conformance quantities and can produce a supplier PPM (parts per million) number used to track supplier quality.

navigationItems.name: Shipping Item Log
navigationItems.documentation: The shipping log is used to document what shippments were made to customers.  This information can be used in conjunction with nonconformance quantities can produce a customer PPM (parts per million) number used to track customer quality.

navigationItems.name: Problem Sources
navigationItems.documentation: Problem sources define where a problem initiates.  Examples of problem sources are: Customer, Inspection, or Internal Audit.  Typically the structured problem solving process would be: Identify, Contain, Root Cause, Corrective Action and Verification.

navigationItems.name: Problem Symptoms
navigationItems.documentation: Problem symptoms allow you to define a standard list of symptoms for a problem category.  Using a define list allows for easier and more consistent analysis of problems.

navigationItems.name: Problem Severities
navigationItems.documentation: Problem severities are used when enter and dispositioning a problem to identify how severe the problem is to the customer.  Severity can then be used as part of the criteria of identifying the most important problems to solve first.

navigationItems.name: Problem Dispositions
navigationItems.documentation: Problem disposition allow you to document a list of dispositions that are possible for a problem category.  Dispositions determine how to handle nonconforming product or processes.  Each disposition also allows you to define a set of approvers who are required to approve the disposition action.

navigationItems.name: Problem Causes
navigationItems.documentation: Problem causes allow you to define a standard list of causes for a problem category.  Using a define list allows for easier and more consistent analysis of problems.

navigationItems.name: Non-conformances Category
navigationItems.documentation: A method to group and control non-conformances by similar categories, such as Customer, Supplier, Process, Product, etc.  The default champion can be set up for each category.  Each non-conformance can belong to one category.

navigationItems.name: Lessons Learned Category
navigationItems.documentation: A method to group lessons learned by category to help facilitate searching by employees.  Each lesson learned can belong to one category.

navigationItems.name: Improvements Categories
navigationItems.documentation: A method to group improvements by category to help facilitate searching by employees.  The default champion can be set up for each category, as well as an option to allow anonymous submissions. Each lesson learned can belong to one category.

navigationItems.name: Improvements Impacts
navigationItems.documentation: Defines a list of common areas or functions that may be impacted by an improvement.  When submitting a new improvement, users can select one or more of these impacts that they think may change based on the improvement.  Actual impacts can then be selected after the completion of the improvement.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment
navigationItems.documentation: Equipment allows you to document the pieces of equipment in the organization.  Typically the equipment also contains the associated maintenance information, both preventive and reactive for tracking purposes.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Work Orders Reactive
navigationItems.documentation: Maintenance work orders are used to assign and document the results of both preventive and reactive mainteance for assests.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Work Orders Preventive
navigationItems.description: Preventative maintenance work orders for specific equipment
navigationItems.documentation: Preventive maintenance work orders are used to assign and document preventive maintenance work for equipment.  Preventive maintenance is an important part of ensuring manufacturing is not interrupted by malfunctioning equipment.

navigationItems.name: Asset Usage Log
navigationItems.documentation: The asset usage log documents usage for assets such as equipment and gauges.  The information entered into the log can then be used with asset meters to create preventive maintenance work orders.

navigationItems.name: Cost Logs
navigationItems.documentation: Cost Log records document the occurrence of a cost to the organization, typically for helping to determine a cost of quality metric.  A cost log entry can be made from several processes including Maintenance Work Orders and Containment Actions.

navigationItems.name: Asset Meters
navigationItems.documentation: Asset meters define the information required to gather data about the usage of an asset.  Asset meters can be associated with one or more assets, such as equipment, and can then be used to define when preventive maintenance should occur based on meter thresholds.  Examples of asset meters are: number of parts produced, number of hours used, or a vechicle's odometer reading.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Teams
navigationItems.documentation: Maintenance teams allow you to create a group of people who can be assigned maintenance work orders.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment Status
navigationItems.documentation: Gauge status' define the list of acceptable status for a gauge.  Each status allows you to define if the gauge will be considered active or inactive that will automatically set the state of the gauge to active or inactive.  Examples of gauge status' might include: Out for Calibration, Missing, or Scrapped.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment Types
navigationItems.documentation: Equipment types allow you to categorize equipment that have similar characteristics.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Fault Codes
navigationItems.documentation: Maintenance fault codes are used to identify why equipment failed during production.  By identifying why a machine failed during reactive maintenance, this information can later be analyzed to improve preventive maintenance on equipment.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Work Order Types
navigationItems.documentation: Maintenance work order types allow you to define high level groups of maintenance work orders to help with planning and assignment.  Some examples might be Preventive Maintenance, Electrical, or Mechanical.

navigationItems.name: Maintenance Work Order Types Resp
navigationItems.description: This process is intended to store responsibility for work orders created for the type

navigationItems.name: Cost Accounts
navigationItems.documentation: Cost accounts are typically tied to the general ledger and allow you to associate costs with the groups defined on the general ledger for cost tracking purposes.

navigationItems.name: Programs
navigationItems.documentation: Programs are used to define a standardized list of program codes and names. Programs are typically created by large organizations to identify a large project that many include many smaller projects. In the automotive vertical, often you'll see programs associated with future model builds of a particular vehicle, such as the 2020 Ford Bronco.

navigationItems.name: Programs
navigationItems.documentation: Programs are used to define a standardized list of program codes and names. Programs are typically created by large organizations to identify a large project that many include many smaller projects. In the automotive vertical, often you'll see programs associated with future model builds of a particular vehicle, such as the 2020 Ford Bronco.

navigationItems.name: Tooling and Equipment Types
navigationItems.documentation: Equipment types allow you to categorize equipment that have similar characteristics.

navigationItems.name: RFQ Proposal
navigationItems.description: A primary process for the Buyer role. Here, the buyer selects a supplier to recommend to the Sourcing Council. The system ranks each completed supplier response for a specific part by quality, delivery, and price. It calculates proposal data automatically and provides a Proposal Analysis Report.
navigationItems.documentation: A primary process for the Buyer role. Here, the buyer selects a supplier to recommend to the Sourcing Council. The system ranks each completed supplier response for a specific part by quality, delivery, and price. It calculates proposal data automatically and provides a Proposal Analysis Report.

navigationItems.name: Sourcing Recommendations
navigationItems.description: The Sourcing Recommendations for sourcing process will be presented for the Commodity being purchased and will contain all RFQ proposals that have been approved for sourcing at the time that the sourcing plans is created for the commodity (Item Group). The Sourcing committee will review each RFQ proposal and either approve the proposal (in which case the RFQ award will be created for the supplier/Item combination) or reject the RFQ Proposals (In which case the buyer will either set up another quotation round for the supplier candidates or cancel the RFQ process and restart the RFQ Process).
navigationItems.documentation: The Sourcing Recommendations for sourcing process will be presented for the Commodity being purchased and will contain all RFQ proposals that have been approved for sourcing at the time that the sourcing plans is created for the commodity (Item Group). The Sourcing committee will review each RFQ proposal and either approve the proposal (in which case the RFQ award will be created for the supplier/Item combination) or reject the RFQ Proposals (In which case the buyer will either set up another quotation round for the supplier candidates or cancel the RFQ process and restart the RFQ Process).

navigationItems.name: Program Awards
navigationItems.description: Allows purchasing agents to manage the awards process to ensure that the supplier has signed of on the award (including the part or parts award and tooling PO's is appropriate). The process will also allow a project to be launched that will link the RFQ application to the APQP app. for seamless integration
navigationItems.documentation: Allows purchasing agents to manage the awards process to ensure that the supplier has signed of on the award (including the part or parts award and tooling PO's is appropriate). The process will also allow a project to be launched that will link the RFQ application to the APQP app. for seamless integration.

navigationItems.name: Risks
navigationItems.documentation: Risks allow you to document the "effect of uncertainity on objectives" that are an integral part of many risk management standards.  After identifying the approproate risks, you can then analyze and evaluate the risk to determine if the if their particular state warrants additional risk treatment or controls to be put in place.

navigationItems.name: Risk Assessments
navigationItems.documentation: Risk assessments allow you to group the identification, analysis and evaluation of risks into a group for easier management.  A risk assessment could be for varying levels within the organization from an overall organization perspective down to an assessment of an individual process.

navigationItems.name: Risk Acceptability Matrix
navigationItems.documentation: The risk accetability matrix defines the general acceptability of the combination of two risk ratings.  In most cases the risk ratings would be Likelihood and Consequence, therefore a matrix line item would set the acceptibility level for the combination of the Likelihood and Consequence selected.

navigationItems.name: Risk Ratings
navigationItems.documentation: Risk ratings allow you to define a list of ratings that can be used for different risk rating types to common a risk for analysis throughout the organization.  The typical example of risk rating types are Likelihood and Consequence.  Many times risk ratings are between one and five, where five is the most likely to occur or the highest consequence if it does occur.  A matrix can then be established between the two criteria and a definition of risk acceptance can be defined for each value.

navigationItems.name: Suppliers
navigationItems.documentation: Suppliers allow you to document information about your suppliers.

navigationItems.name: Deviations
navigationItems.description: Documentation for deviations on controlled specifications or processes.
navigationItems.documentation: Deviations are used to document and approve changes to the standards used by the organization.  A deviation generally affects an item or a process, changing temporarily one or more specifications associated with the item or the way the process is completed.  Deviations can then be approved either internally and/or by the customer to begin the change.  Typically, deviations then expire based on time or when a certain number of items have been produced under the deviation.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Performance Reviews
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier performance reviews are used to document the results of supplier performance indicators at a point in time.  Based on the criteria setup for the supplier's risk category, the total score of the performance review is used to automatically calculate the supplier's approval status.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Audits
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier audits are used to conduct full or partial quality system or other management system standard audits of a supplier.  In some occasions a supplier audit is required in order for a supplier to become certifeid to supplier to an organization, depending on what commodities are supplied.  Supplier audits don't typically update the supplier approval rating (supplier reviews are used for that) but they may be an input into the supplier review process.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Corrective Action Request
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier corrective action requests allow you to issue and track the status of corrective actions that have been issued to suppliers.

navigationItems.name: PO Item Log
navigationItems.documentation: The po itme log is used to document what receipts were made from suppliers.  This information can be used in conjunction with nonconformance quantities can produce a supplier PPM (parts per million) number used to track supplier quality.

navigationItems.name: Receiving Item Log
navigationItems.documentation: The receiving item log is used to document receipts from suppliers.  This information can be used in conjunction with non-conformance quantities and can produce a supplier PPM (parts per million) number used to track supplier quality.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Certifications
navigationItems.description: This process is intended for tracking the current certifications carried by a supplier (e.g. ISO 9000, TS 16949).

navigationItems.name: Supplier Items
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier items allow you to document the relationship between an Item and a Supplier.  The relationship allows you to also indicate additional information such as the supplier's catalog or item number as well as a standard price.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Audit Checklists
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier audit checklists allow you to group one or more supplier audit questions so that you can more easily select which questions to ask for a supplier audit by simply selecting the checklist.  Often there may be several supplier audit checklists for use in auditing different parts of the supplier organization, for example Manufacturing processes, Receiving processes, or Shipping processes.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Audit Questions
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier audit questions allow you to build up a library of questions for supplier's to respond to during a supplier audit.  Having a library of questions provides a consistency between supplier audits, especially when several different people are conducting supplier audits.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Approval Status
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier approval status are used to identify which suppliers are approved for purchasing activities and which are not.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Risk Categories
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier risk categories define a level of risk that is associated with each supplier.  Based on a risk category, supplier performance targets can be set as well as the frequency at which supplier reviews and audits are scheduled.

navigationItems.name: Supplier Performance Indicators
navigationItems.documentation: Supplier performance indicators allow you to setup the values that will be used to evaluate the performance of the suppliers.  Each indicator allows you to define the description, score ratings and weight applied.  When conducting a supplier performance review the indicators will provide the basis of completed the review.

navigationItems.name: Certification Agencies
navigationItems.description: This process is intended to store certification agencies such as ISO which will be used to feed cross references in Supplier Certifications.

navigationItems.name: Employees
navigationItems.description: Employee Skills & General Information
navigationItems.documentation: Employees document the information for each employee in the organization.  Each employee can also have their training information documented as part of the employee record.

navigationItems.name: Employee Skills
navigationItems.description: Skills, skill requirements and ratings assigned to individual Employees.
navigationItems.documentation: Employee skills define the relationship between an Employee and a Skill, including what the current rating is, last trained, and expiration information.  An employee can have multiple of the same skill if they have more than one role that defines a requirement for that skill, in this case the skill will be listed each time a role has a requirement for the skill.  The employee skill list can be filtered to determine which employees need training on which skills.

navigationItems.name: Training Events
navigationItems.description: Events that evaluate employee skills
navigationItems.documentation: Training events allow you to track scheduled and completed training in the organization.  Training people is a vital part of any management system and training events allow that training to be scheduled and completed.

navigationItems.name: Training Event Logs
navigationItems.description: Individual training records for employee/skill combinations.
navigationItems.documentation: The training event log stores all of the historical training that an employee has completed.  This process also is used to have the person trained answer some training evaluation questions to ensure that they training they received was properly understood.

navigationItems.name: Employee Events
navigationItems.description: General events related to employee development
navigationItems.documentation: Employee events allow you to document significant events throughout the history of an employee at the organization.  The two main examples of employee events are on-boarding (when an employee joins the organization) and separation (when an employee leaves the organization.)

navigationItems.name: Employee Certifications
navigationItems.description: Certification information for Training Roles
navigationItems.documentation: Employee Certifications are used to document the certification process for a Training Role.  Typically the certification process involves the employee being reviewed by a training lead or supervisor over the course of several certification events, in the end if the employee performed well at each of the events, the employee would be deemed as certified.

navigationItems.name: Employee Titles
navigationItems.description: The Employee's Position and Training Role requiements
navigationItems.documentation: Employee Titles are used to define a position within the organization, along with which Employee Roles are required for the position.  Additional information such as Job Responsibilities and Educational / Training Requirements can be defined as well for a title, allowing to be used as the full definition of the title for employee review and hiring activities.

navigationItems.name: Training Roles
navigationItems.description: Groups of skill requirements related to employee training.
navigationItems.documentation: Training roles define a specific role in the organization, along with what skills are required for the role.  An Employee Title or position then has one or more required roles that should be able to be performed to be employed at that position, which in turn defines the required set of skills for an Employee based on their Title.

navigationItems.name: Skills
navigationItems.description: Individual learning activities or abilities
navigationItems.documentation: Skills allow you to document the different learning activities or abilities within the organization.

navigationItems.name: Employee Security Groups
navigationItems.documentation: Defines what security groups an Employee has.  When a security group is added to an Employee, then Employee automatically gets all of the security roles associated with the security group.

navigationItems.name: Skill Types
navigationItems.documentation: Skill types allow you to organization skills into different categories.  Some examples of skill types may be: Communication, Interpersonal, Analytical, Teamwork, or Management.

navigationItems.name: Skill Ratings
navigationItems.documentation: Skill ratings describe the different levels of proficiencies for a skill.

navigationItems.name: Training Event Types
navigationItems.description: Categorizes and sets default approval information for Training Events.
navigationItems.documentation: Training event types allow you to create categories for training events as well as determine whether or not approval will be required at the training event level, training log (attendee) level or both.

navigationItems.name: Employee Event Types
navigationItems.description: Default settings and checklists for employee events
navigationItems.documentation: Employee event types allow you to organize employee events.  Examples of event types are On-boarding or Separation.

navigationItems.name: Certification Performance Measures
navigationItems.documentation: Certification Performance Measures allow you to document a general list of performance measures that may potentially be used to document an employee's performance as part of a certification event.  This list is just the performance measure's name and description, the actual values that should be achieved as part of a certification event will be set at the Training Role level.

navigationItems.name: Certification Event Frequencies
navigationItems.documentation: Certification Event Frequencies define a generic list of frequencies at which employee certification events can occur.  Examples of frequencies might be 30 days, 60 days, 90 days, and recertification.

navigationItems.name: Review Frequencies
navigationItems.description: Frequencies that drive review requirements
navigationItems.documentation: Review frequencies are used to create re-usable frequencies for items that expire, for example skill re-training or document review.  Upon expiration, action messages are often generated to the appropriate personnel to determine the next steps for the item should be.  For skill re-training, this may mean to create a training event and train the employees who require training.  For a document review, this may mean to either update the document to make it more relevant or make it obsolete if it's no longer used.

navigationItems.name: Skill Training Questions
navigationItems.description: Questions used in training events to evaluate skill levels.
navigationItems.documentation: Skill training questions allow you to define a set of questions for a skill that are asked after a training event on the skill to see if participants gained the required knowledge about the skill.  Skill training questions can also be defined for a specific document revision to ensure that changes made to a document have been properly transferred to individuals requiring knowledge of a document change.
